Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

- Mike Whatley, 1952 Roosevelt Avenue, Two Rivers, WI.

BAIL HEARING - 
Defendant in custody and appearing by video from the Manitowoc County Jail.  The State informs the Court that the defendant will be charged with the crimes of felony bail jumping and disorderly conduct.  The matters are continued for initial appearance on 10-10-22 at 1:30 pm in Branch 1.  Bail is set at $200 cash with the conditions that the defendant is to have no contact with any establishment whose primary purpose is the sale of alcohol, the defendant is to have no contact with any taverns, and the defendant must maintain absolute sobriety.   Bail furnished and defendant is released from custody.
